+# MNE-Python Module Import Hierarchy
+
+This document describes the module import hierarchy in MNE-Python and guidelines for maintaining a clean import structure without circular dependencies.
+
+## Import Hierarchy Levels
+
+The MNE-Python codebase is organized into dependency levels. Modules at higher levels can import from lower levels, but not vice versa without using deferred imports.
+
+### Level 0: External Dependencies
+- NumPy, SciPy, matplotlib, and other third-party packages
+- Python standard library
+
+### Level 1: Foundation (No internal dependencies)
+- `mne.utils/` - Logging, configuration, numerics, testing utilities
+- `mne.fixes` - Compatibility fixes for different library versions
+- `mne.defaults` - Default values and constants
+- `mne._fiff/constants` - FIFF format constants
+
+### Level 2: Low-Level I/O and Structures
+- `mne._fiff/` - Low-level FIFF file operations (tag reading/writing, tree operations)
+- `mne.transforms` - Coordinate transformation utilities
+- `mne.surface` - Surface manipulation functions
+- `mne.baseline` - Baseline correction utilities
+- `mne.filter` - Signal filtering functions
+
+### Level 3: Core Data Structures
+- `mne.io.base` - BaseRaw and base I/O classes
+- `mne.io.meas_info` - Measurement info structure
+- `mne.epochs` - BaseEpochs for epoched data
+- `mne.evoked` - Evoked response data
+- `mne.cov` - Covariance matrices
+- `mne.bem` - Boundary element models
+- `mne.source_space` - Source space definitions
+- `mne.source_estimate` - Source estimates (SourceEstimate, etc.)
+- `mne.dipole` - Dipole fitting and models
+
+### Level 4: I/O Implementations
+- `mne.io.fiff/` - FIFF format reader/writer
+- `mne.io.brainvision/`, `mne.io.edf/`, etc. - Format-specific readers
+- All other `mne.io.*` submodules
+
+### Level 5: Processing and Analysis
+- `mne.channels/` - Channel operations, montages, layouts
+- `mne.preprocessing/` - ICA, SSP, Maxwell filtering, artifact correction
+- `mne.forward/` - Forward modeling
+- `mne.time_frequency/` - Time-frequency analysis (TFR, CSD, etc.)
+- `mne.beamformer/` - Beamformer methods
+- `mne.minimum_norm/` - Minimum norm estimation
+- `mne.inverse_sparse/` - Sparse inverse solutions
+- `mne.decoding/` - Machine learning decoders
+
+### Level 6: Visualization and High-Level Operations
+- `mne.viz/` - All visualization functions
+- `mne.stats/` - Statistical analysis
+- `mne.simulation/` - Data simulation
+- `mne.report/` - Report generation
+
+### Level 7: User Interface
+- `mne.commands/` - Command-line interface tools
+
+## Circular Import Patterns
+
+Despite careful hierarchy design, some bidirectional dependencies are necessary for functionality. These are handled using **deferred imports** (importing inside functions rather than at module level).
+
+### Known Circular Dependencies (All Properly Handled)
+
+#### 1. evoked.py ↔ dipole.py
+- **Location**: `mne/evoked.py:_write_evokeds()`
+- **Reason**: Evoked data can contain dipole fits; dipoles can be created from evoked data
+- **Solution**: Import `DipoleFixed` inside `_write_evokeds()` function
+
+#### 2. evoked.py ↔ io.base
+- **Location**: `mne/evoked.py:Evoked.get_data()`
+- **Reason**: Evoked uses I/O utilities; I/O base classes use evoked operations
+- **Solution**: Import `_get_ch_factors` inside `get_data()` method
+
+#### 3. epochs.py ↔ io.base
+- **Location**: `mne/epochs.py:BaseEpochs._get_data()`
+- **Reason**: Similar to evoked, shared utilities between epochs and I/O
+- **Solution**: Import `_get_ch_factors` inside `_get_data()` method
+
+#### 4. forward._make_forward ↔ dipole
+- **Location**: `mne/forward/_make_forward.py:make_forward_dipole()`
+- **Reason**: Forward models use dipoles; dipoles use forward modeling
+- **Solution**: Import `_concatenate_dipoles` inside `make_forward_dipole()`
+
+#### 5. channels.channels ↔ io.BaseRaw / epochs.BaseEpochs
+- **Locations**: Multiple methods in `mne/channels/channels.py`
+- **Reason**: Channel operations need type checking for Raw/Epochs; Raw/Epochs inherit channel mixins
+- **Solution**: Deferred imports in methods that need type checking
+
+#### 6. time_frequency.csd ↔ cov.Covariance
+- **Locations**: `mne/time_frequency/csd.py` (multiple methods)
+- **Reason**: CSD matrices can be converted to covariance matrices and vice versa
+- **Solution**: Import `Covariance` in methods like `get_data()` and `__setstate__()`
+
+#### 7. viz.ica ↔ io.BaseRaw / evoked.Evoked
+- **Location**: `mne/viz/ica.py` (plotting functions)
+- **Reason**: Visualization needs to handle multiple data types
+- **Solution**: Deferred imports in plot functions
+
+#### 8. _fiff.pick ↔ _fiff.meas_info
+- **Location**: `mne/_fiff/pick.py:pick_info()`
+- **Reason**: Mutual dependencies within low-level FIFF operations
+- **Solution**: Deferred import in `pick_info()`
+
+## Guidelines for Developers
+
+### When Adding New Code
+
+1. **Follow the hierarchy**: Import from lower levels only
+2. **Use deferred imports for circular dependencies**: If you must create a circular dependency, use deferred imports with a clear comment
+3. **Document circular imports**: Always add a comment explaining why the deferred import is necessary
+4. **Prefer composition over inheritance**: Reduces coupling between modules
+5. **Use lazy loading**: For package-level imports, consider using `lazy_loader`
+
+### Deferred Import Pattern
+
+```python
+def my_function():
+    # Import DipoleFixed here to avoid circular import:
+    # evoked.py imports from dipole.py and vice versa
+    from .dipole import DipoleFixed
+
+    # Function implementation
+    ...
+```
+
+### Comment Format
+
+Use one of these standardized formats:
+- `# Avoid circular import` (short form)
+- `# Import here to avoid circular import: module_a ↔ module_b` (descriptive)
+- `# Deferred import: [module_name]` (if the circular dependency is obvious from context)
+
+### Type Hinting with Circular Dependencies
+
+Use `TYPE_CHECKING` for type hints:
+
+```python
+from typing import TYPE_CHECKING
+
+if TYPE_CHECKING:
+    from .epochs import BaseEpochs
+
+def process_data(data: 'BaseEpochs') -> None:
+    # Implementation uses deferred import if needed
+    ...
+```
+
+## Lazy Loading
+
+MNE-Python uses the `lazy_loader` library for package-level lazy loading. This defers submodule imports until first access, reducing import time and helping avoid circular imports.
+
+### Modules Using Lazy Loading
+
+- `mne/` (main package)
+- `mne/io/`
+- `mne/viz/`
+- `mne/preprocessing/`
+- `mne/forward/`
+- `mne/channels/`
+- `mne/utils/`
+- `mne/time_frequency/`
+- `mne/beamformer/`
+- `mne/minimum_norm/`
+- `mne/inverse_sparse/`
+- `mne/decoding/`
+- `mne/simulation/`
+- `mne/datasets/`
+- `mne/commands/`
+- `mne/stats/`
+- `mne/report/`
+- And others (see individual `__init__.py` files)
+
+## Testing Import Structure
+
+To verify there are no circular import issues at module level:
+
+```bash
+# Test basic imports
+python -c "import mne"
+
+# Test specific modules
+python -c "import mne.evoked; import mne.dipole"
+python -c "import mne.epochs; import mne.io.base"
+
+# Run the full test suite
+pytest mne/tests/
+```
+
+## Maintenance
+
+When refactoring:
+
+1. **Check for circular dependencies**: Run import tests after changes
+2. **Update this document**: If you change the module structure or resolve circular imports
+3. **Keep deferred imports minimal**: Only use when necessary
+4. **Consider extracting shared code**: If two modules both need the same functionality, consider creating a lower-level utility module
+
+## Tools
+
+Use these tools to analyze imports:
+
+```python
+# Check for top-level circular imports
+python -c "
+import ast, os
+from collections import defaultdict
+
+# ... (see /testbed/tools/check_circular_imports.py if created)
+"
+```
+
+## References
+
+- [PEP 8 - Style Guide for Python Code](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#imports)
+- [lazy_loader documentation](https://github.com/scientific-python/lazy_loader)
+- Python's `importlib` for understanding import mechanics
